WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Here's one way to think about journalism. It's a business driven by supply and demand.

00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:15.600
[Amit Varma]: People want news, analysis, narratives, whatever. You form a publication that delivers and cater

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:20.880
[Amit Varma]: to what readers want. Your bottom line is the bottom line. Your dharma, as it were,

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:25.400
[Amit Varma]: is to your shareholders. Principles matter only to the extent that principles are in

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:30.680
[Amit Varma]: demand. You gotta be rational. You gotta stay solvent. That's one way of looking at it.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:35.240
[Amit Varma]: But there are other impulses that can drive journalists. You can say that truth matters,

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:39.760
[Amit Varma]: especially in these polarized and complex times, and that searching for the truth has

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:44.120
[Amit Varma]: a value of its own. You can be driven by the urge to tell stories about the world that

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:48.800
[Amit Varma]: would otherwise be lost in the din. You can tell yourself that the world is often shaped

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:53.480
[Amit Varma]: by what we know of it. And therefore, it is important to seek out the full picture. And

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:57.560
[Amit Varma]: you may believe that enough people share this view for it to be worthwhile, for the bottom

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:02.160
[Amit Varma]: line also to be taken care of. As you would have guessed, I believe in the second school

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:06.120
[Amit Varma]: of thought. I believe we don't always have to follow our audiences and second guess what

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:10.760
[Amit Varma]: the political masters of this country may want. I believe journalists and storytellers

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:16.560
[Amit Varma]: can lead from the front, can form public opinion by informing public opinion, by relentlessly

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:21.080
[Amit Varma]: deepening our understanding of the truth. I admire the handful of people committed to

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:27.360
[Amit Varma]: this quest. One of them is my guest today.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:32.560
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:39.840
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Barkha Dutt, a fearless and pioneering

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:49.840
[Amit Varma]: television journalist who's seen it all. She's been at the frontline of wars, terrorist attacks

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.640
[Amit Varma]: and pandemics. While others sit at home and pontificate or signal their virtue or wisdom

00:01:54.640 --> 00:02:00.420
[Amit Varma]: on social media, Barkha goes out there and reports. She started in NDTV and after more

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:05.560
[Amit Varma]: than two decades there, has ended up forming Mojo Story, an indie outfit that is breaking

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:11.120
[Amit Varma]: new ground on YouTube. Her coverage of the pandemic over the last 16 months has been

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:16.800
[Amit Varma]: incredible. I enjoy chatting with Barkha and we spoke not just about journalism, the media,

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:22.360
[Amit Varma]: Indian politics and society, but also about her own self, how she has grown, what she

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.640
[Amit Varma]: has learned, how she now looks at the world and her place in it. She also has some great

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:29.760
[Amit Varma]: advice for young people who may be trying to figure out who they are and what they want

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:35.200
[Amit Varma]: to do. Before we begin this conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

